China Stocks: ICBC, PetroChina, Taigang, Zoomlion Heavy, ZTE

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-02-21T07:53:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-20/zoomlion-china-pacific-everbright-bank-china-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 32.45, or 1.1 percent, to 2,932.25.
The  CSI 300 Index  gained 1.4 percent to 3,257.91.  Banking stocks:  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China  Ltd.
(601398 CH), the nation’s biggest listed lender, slipped 0.7
percent to 4.30 yuan. Bank of China Ltd. (601988 CH), the fourth
biggest, lost 0.3 percent to 3.27 yuan.  The central bank ordered lenders to set aside more money as
reserves for the second time this year. Reserve ratios will
climb half a percentage point effective Feb. 24, the People’s
Bank of China said after the market close Feb. 18.  Oil-related stocks: PetroChina Co. (601857 CH), the
nation’s biggest oil company, gained 1.1 percent to 11.71 yuan.
China Petroleum & Chemical Corp. (600028 CH), the second biggest,
rose 1.4 percent to 9.27 yuan.  China increased retail gasoline and diesel prices for the
first time this year, aiding state refiners under pressure after
crude rose above $100 a barrel. Gasoline and diesel yesterday
rose by 350 yuan ($53) a ton, or as much as 4.6 percent, the
National Development and Reform Commission, the top economic
planner, said over the week-end.  Changsha Zoomlion Heavy Industry Science and Technology
Development Co. (000157 CH), China’s second-biggest maker of
construction equipment, climbed 2.5 percent to 14.94 yuan. The
company said it plans to invest 100 million yuan to set up an
insurance company whose size is tentatively set at 1.15 billion
yuan in  Hunan province .  China State Construction Engineering Corp. (601668 CH), the
nation’s largest housing contractor, rose 1.4 percent to 3.71
yuan. The company said it signed 42.8 billion yuan of new
construction contracts in January, an increase of 81.4 percent
compared with a year earlier. Property sales rose 92 percent to
7.5 billion yuan last month.  Shanxi Taigang Stainless Steel Co. (000825 CH), China’s
biggest producer of the rust-proof metal, added 1 percent to
5.88 yuan after saying it will set up a unit for making
specialty steel used in machinery and railways.    ZTE Corp . (000063 CH), China’s second-biggest maker of
phone-network equipment, surged the most since November 2008,
gaining 10 percent to 31.42 yuan. ZTE led telecommunications
companies higher on speculation that the government will
announce measures to boost the industry in the next five-year
economic plan.  “The government’s support will boost earnings in the
industry,” said Zhang Tao, an analyst at Shanghai Securities
Co. “The positive factor stands out amid weak  market
sentiment .”  --Zhang Shidong. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
